@flexiarg ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing
@title Diagnose Before Prescribing
@keywords diagnosis, binding-constraint, population-model, D-times-A, multiplicative-gate, intervention-variance, prior-not-posterior, profile-signature, universal-vs-diagnosed
@audience UKRN-S design, programme commissioners, Research England, institutional leads
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [ukrns/ARGUMENT equity/confident-adaptation ukrns/provision-at-network-scale ukrns/measure-where-least-sure]

! conclusion: A universal service offering is cheap to produce, easy to communicate, and wrong for a visible fraction of the network.  A diagnosed offering names the binding constraint — whether the bottleneck is delivery viability, architectural sustainability, or both — before selecting a service response.  The service states, for any profile, which composition on the universal-vs-diagnosed axis it is running and why.
  + context: The UKRN WP §1 (draft-16-april) derives a two-dimensional factorisation from the Cycle-0 focus groups: delivery viability (D, from Confident Adaptation + Protected Interaction) and architectural sustainability (A, from Shared Maintenance + Contribution Pathways + Visible Impact), related multiplicatively (P(multiplied) = D × A).  The intervention-variance figure (Figure 2) shows empirically that the same lever bundle moves P(multiplied) very differently across profiles.  The equity-domain confident-adaptation pattern diagnoses the informational gap at institutional scale; this design pattern asks, at service scale, whether the programme has identified the binding constraint before choosing a response.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: universal service offering ↔ diagnosed service offering.
    Real: a universal offering is cheap to produce, easy to communicate, and — as Figure 2 shows — wrong for a visible fraction of the network; a diagnosed offering, naming each profile's binding constraint before acting, is more costly to produce, harder to explain, and matched to what each profile actually needs.  Both endpoints carry genuine cost.
    Irreducible: diagnosis and uniformity cannot both be maximised in the same service offering.  A single bundle cannot be simultaneously the lowest-cost-to-run-and-communicate option AND the best-matched option for every profile on the constraint map.
    Active: the axis recurs every time a new cohort arrives, every time an institution joins, every time UKRN-S is asked what it supports.  The right position may drift as the network grows and as the profile map updates with evidence.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Diagnostic-first: run the first T1 wave as a diagnostic pass and let the observed binding-constraint signatures drive subsequent service differentiation.  Gives up early time-to-service.
    (2) Universal bundle: keep the universal service cheap and accept the across-profile variance as the cost of reach.  Gives up per-profile fit.
    (3) Two-tier: a universal baseline for profiles that fall well under the model, and a diagnostic overlay for profiles that flag as multi-constrained.  Gives up single-narrative uniformity; complicates communication.
    These compositions are not ranked; the WP does not prefer one over the others, but does make the axis visible.
  + BECAUSE:
    Multiplicative gate (D × A): The factorisation is the mathematical reason diagnosis matters.  If D and A were additive, a universal bundle would average out across profiles.  Because they multiply, a constraint on either dimension bounds the whole; no amount of lift on the non-binding dimension closes the gap.  This is why 'blame trainer effort' is a systematic misreading: trainers are often the very actors whose dimension is fine, while the binding constraint is elsewhere.

    Cycle-0 empirical evidence: The role-codebook analysis (4/4 transcripts show EV_analyse absent) is a profile-level claim about where the architecture is weak.  The intervention-variance figure makes the per-profile sensitivity to lever choice visible.  The claim is not that diagnosis produces certainty; it is that diagnosis converts an invisible variance into a stated position.

    Prior-not-posterior: The population model is explicit about its epistemic status.  It does not predict what will happen; it makes conditional dependencies inspectable.  The diagnostic move works on priors — and the first T1 wave is the act that begins converting priors to posteriors for the widest-interval profiles (linked: ukrns/measure-where-least-sure).

    Confidence in the diagnosis (equity/confident-adaptation link): The equity pattern's concern at the institutional level — that trainers cannot adapt confidently without knowing what is fixed — has a structural counterpart at the service level.  The service cannot prescribe confidently without knowing what is binding.  Both patterns are specification problems at their own scale.

    Commons governance: An institution assigned to a profile has a stake in whether that assignment is correct.  Publishing the diagnostic reasoning invites the institution into the profiling itself.  A service that assigns profiles without showing reasoning forecloses governance; a service that shows reasoning invites negotiation.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the programme can point to the binding-constraint signature of any profile before prescribing an intervention; profile assignments are published with the D × A evidence that supports them; institutions can contest their assignment.
    Failing when: observed variance in outcomes is explained by trainer effort rather than by the profile's constraint structure; every institution receives the same offering regardless of diagnosis; profile signatures are never revised despite new observations.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Maintain a current profile-signature for each participating institution in the population model
    - Publish the intervention-variance chart for each service cycle so profile assignment is inspectable
    - Before committing a lever bundle to any profile, state the binding constraint and the D × A evidence that supports it
    - Allow institutions to contest their profile signature; revise on evidence, not on complaint
    - Use this pattern upstream of ukrns/provision-at-network-scale (which decides capability scale) and ukrns/measure-where-least-sure (which targets the next observation)
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    No lever bundle is prescribed to any profile without a stated binding-constraint signature and an appeal to the D × A evidence.  The service's current composition on the universal-vs-diagnosed axis is published.  Profile assignments are revisable in light of new observations.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Universal offering: one bundle for all profiles; right for some, wrong for the rest
    - Variance-as-effort: attributing across-profile variance to trainer motivation rather than profile structure
    - Cheap diagnosis: profiles assigned without reference to the D × A evidence
    - Frozen diagnosis: profile signature never revised despite new observations
    - Hidden diagnosis: assignment made internally; institutions see only the lever bundle
    - Politically-convenient diagnosis: profile chosen to justify a preferred lever bundle rather than the other way round
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN WP draft-16-april §1 Pattern (intervention-variance figure; D × A derivation; explicit Tension/Composition/Check)
    - UKRN WP §3 (Table 1 baseline; worked examples FG2A-P1 delivery-gated, FG3-A multiply-constrained; Table 2 credible intervals)
    - Role-codebook analysis: EV_analyse absent 4/4 transcripts; coordination under-provisioned
    - equity/confident-adaptation (diagnoses the institutional specification failure this design pattern answers at service scale)
    - NPT mode tree: P(multiplied) = D × A; P(absorbed) = D × (1-A); P(mismatch) = 1-D
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from UKRN WP draft-16-april §1's factorisation, intervention-variance analysis, and explicit Tension/Composition/Check structure.
    Answers equity/confident-adaptation at service scale: the institutional 'know what is fixed' has a service-level counterpart, 'know what is binding'.
    Mapped to the learning loop at the 'diagnose' step: upstream of provisioning and measurement.
    Deepened via the multiplicative-gate structure: diagnosis is mathematically necessary, not a nicety.
    Axis framing follows paper-draft-16-april; real / irreducible / active defence and three named compositions are load-bearing.
    Coordination requirement: Low for the service (internal analytical act) but requires Medium participation from institutions (profile contestation).
